    stimulus: 'A student is writing an essay arguing that the Atlantic slave trade accelerated the development of new credit instruments in early modern Europe, specifically by creating financial demands that existing systems could not handle. The student has collected the following notes:\n\n• The Atlantic slave trade required merchants to manage complex, multi-year, multi-continental transactions that exceeded the capacity of existing credit systems.\n• Portuguese and Dutch merchants developed new forms of negotiable bills of exchange specifically to finance slaving voyages, allowing debts to be transferred between creditors across national boundaries.\n• Insurance markets in London and Amsterdam expanded significantly in the seventeenth century, in part due to demand for coverage of cargo aboard slaving ships.\n• The Royal African Company, chartered in 1672, was among the earliest joint-stock companies to raise capital from investors for large-scale mercantile operations.\n• Mortality rates among enslaved people during the Middle Passage averaged between 10% and 20% depending on voyage duration and conditions.',
    question: 'Which choice most effectively uses the notes to argue that the trade\'s financial demands accelerated the development of new credit instruments?',
    choices: [
      { label: 'A', text: 'The Atlantic slave trade operated across three continents and subjected enslaved people to mortality rates of 10–20% during the Middle Passage, illustrating the scale and human cost of the trade.' },
      { label: 'B', text: 'Because existing credit systems could not accommodate the trade\'s multi-year, multi-continental transactions, merchants developed negotiable bills of exchange and expanded insurance markets to manage the financial demands that those systems could not fulfill.' },
      { label: 'C', text: 'The Royal African Company raised capital from investors as a joint-stock company, while Portuguese and Dutch merchants developed negotiable bills of exchange, both of which reshaped early modern European finance.' },
      { label: 'D', text: 'Insurance markets in London and Amsterdam grew substantially in the seventeenth century, partly due to demand from the Atlantic slave trade, demonstrating that European financial institutions profited from the trade.' },
    ],
    correctAnswer: 'B',
    explanation: 'The task requires a causal argument: financial demands exceeded existing systems, so new instruments were developed. Choice B explicitly states the cause (existing systems could not handle multi-year, multi-continental transactions) and the effects (merchants developed bills of exchange; insurance markets expanded), linking cause to effect with the word "because." This is the only choice that constructs the required causal argument. Choice A uses the scale and mortality notes, which address the trade\'s human cost rather than credit instrument development. Choice C lists two financial developments but omits the causal link — the demand exceeding existing systems — leaving only a list of facts. Choice D attributes insurance market growth to profit rather than to financial demands exceeding existing capacity, making a different argument.',
    wrongAnswerExplanations: {
      A: 'Scale and mortality data describe the trade\'s scope and human cost; they do not address how financial demands drove the development of new credit instruments.',
      C: 'This lists two financial developments accurately but does not connect them to the trade\'s demands exceeding existing credit systems — the causal argument the student wants to make is absent.',
      D: 'Framing insurance growth as evidence that institutions "profited" makes a different argument than the one about financial demands accelerating development of new instruments.',
    },
    teachingPoint: 'When asked to make a specific causal argument ("accelerated by demands"), the correct answer must name both the cause (demands exceeding existing capacity) and the effects (specific instruments developed), joined by an explicit causal connector. Choices that accurately list effects without the causal chain do not fulfill the argument.',
    relatedSkills: ['Central Ideas and Details', 'Transitions'],
